WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.350
&gt;&gt; Let's get right
to the business

00:00:14.350 --> 00:00:20.160
of why we're really here, what
you see here, Kim Roberts.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:23.880
She is the author of "A Literary
Guide to Washington, DC:

00:00:23.880 --> 00:00:27.400
Walking in the Footsteps
of American Writers"

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:31.790
from Francis Scott Key to Zora
Neale Hurston and we are--

00:00:31.790 --> 00:00:36.810
and usually having books in
the back for sale and there's

00:00:36.810 --> 00:00:38.930
at the-- we're being
offered a reduced rate.

00:00:38.930 --> 00:00:41.830
And of course since we're the
Library of Congress it's also,

00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:44.380
you know, [inaudible],
so that's always nice.

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:48.370
So you guys have got
very [inaudible] entity.

00:00:48.370 --> 00:00:53.860
And we also-- After the
talk we will have a display.

00:00:53.860 --> 00:00:57.490
But she is the author of this
book and five books of poems,

00:00:57.490 --> 00:01:01.460
most recently "The
Scientific Method",

00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:04.680
"WordTech Editions" from 2017.

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:08.210
She co-edits the
"Beltway Poetry Quarterly"

00:01:08.210 --> 00:01:11.640
and the web exhibit,
DC Writers' Homes.

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:14.270
Roberts has been the
recipient of grants

00:01:14.270 --> 00:01:18.450
from the National
Endowment of the Humanities

00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:21.800
and the DC Commission for the
Arts and has been a writer

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:25.940
in residence at 18
different artist colonies.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:27.340
Poems of hers have been featured

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:31.290
in the Wick Poetry Center's
Traveling Stanzas project

00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:35.570
on the Academy of American
Poets Poem a Day Project

00:01:35.570 --> 00:01:38.220
and on podcast sponsored
by the Library of Congress

00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:42.340
and the National
Endowment for the Arts.

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:46.530
I also will say that she-- I
had a little bit of a preview

00:01:46.530 --> 00:01:51.030
of this because when the
SHARP 2011 Conference came

00:01:51.030 --> 00:01:54.140
to Washington, DC, we
often have excursions

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:58.510
and I had Kim do a tour
of the [inaudible] Carter

00:01:58.510 --> 00:02:02.340
and the African-American
literary culture here

00:02:02.340 --> 00:02:07.470
that was very well received, and
we had many people attend that.

00:02:07.470 --> 00:02:11.530
And also, both Sabrina
and I, I don't think--

00:02:11.530 --> 00:02:15.430
But I know Kim from
graduate school,

00:02:15.430 --> 00:02:17.100
University of Maryland, too.

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:21.510
So let's welcome Kim
Roberts and [inaudible].

00:02:21.510 --> 00:02:26.170
[ Applause ]

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:29.420
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Thank
you so much.

00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:40.360
It's an honor to be able to
speak before you and thank you,

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:43.830
Eleanor, and also in
her absence thank you

00:02:43.830 --> 00:02:48.480
to Sabrina for organizing this.

00:02:48.480 --> 00:02:52.540
So my book tells the story
of Washington, DC's writers

00:02:52.540 --> 00:02:55.140
from the founding
of the city in 1800

00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:57.570
to just the beginnings
of modernism.

00:02:57.570 --> 00:03:00.300
I stop around 1930.

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:03.900
It combines four
neighborhood walking tours

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:07.030
with brief portraits of
individual writers of note.

00:03:07.030 --> 00:03:08.790
Some of these writers
will be familiar

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:10.560
to any well read American

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:14.580
but many will I hope
be new discoveries.

00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:20.690
I decided to focus on the city's
early history because I thought

00:03:20.690 --> 00:03:22.960
that those were the stories
that were less well known,

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:26.570
they certainly were
to me initially.

00:03:26.570 --> 00:03:30.420
I've organized the book into
five chapters corresponding

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:33.440
to five, sometimes
overlapping time periods

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:35.020
that marked the eras
of the most [inaudible]

00:03:35.020 --> 00:03:38.520
in the city's early
literary communities.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:40.430
Chapter 1 has no walking tour

00:03:40.430 --> 00:03:44.030
but all the other chapters
combine a tour with portraits.

00:03:44.030 --> 00:03:46.840
The book also serves as
an anthology with poems

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:50.930
and prose excerpts from
each featured author.

00:03:52.070 --> 00:03:54.410
So I thought I'd focus
today on eight writers

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:56.920
from the book starting
with the author

00:03:56.920 --> 00:03:59.970
of our country's
national anthem.

00:03:59.970 --> 00:04:03.870
A lawyer and DC's
former district attorney,

00:04:03.870 --> 00:04:07.150
Francis Scott Key was
a hobbyist writer.

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:10.060
His only remembered poem was
published originally as the

00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:13.030
"Defence of Fort
M'Henry" and Key wrote it

00:04:13.030 --> 00:04:15.640
after witnessing the bombing of
Fort McHenry during the Battle

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:18.780
of Baltimore in the war of 1812.

00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:21.520
Ironically, when it was set to
music, it was set to the tune

00:04:21.520 --> 00:04:25.090
of a then popular British
drinking song called

00:04:25.090 --> 00:04:27.660
"To Anacreon In Heaven".

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:31.510
In addition to occasional poems
that were collected into a book

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:34.740
that was published 14
years after his death,

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:38.290
Key published a nonfiction
book, the power of literature

00:04:38.290 --> 00:04:41.130
and its connection
with religion.

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:45.090
Key lived in two
locations in DC,

00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:48.170
the Maples at 619
D Street Northwest

00:04:48.170 --> 00:04:51.110
on Capitol Hill still stands,
although it's been broken

00:04:51.110 --> 00:04:53.880
up into multiple
condominium units.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:05:01.120
Another property that it's shown
on this slide was once located

00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:02.530
on M Street in Georgetown.

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:05.640
It was made into a museum
celebrating the author

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:09.800
but it was torn down when
Key Bridge was constructed.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:11.160
However, across the street

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:13.210
from that house location
there's now a park

00:05:13.210 --> 00:05:15.010
with a bust of the author.

00:05:15.010 --> 00:05:17.540
In addition to the bridge
and the little park,

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:20.580
Key Elementary School, part
of the DC public school system

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:24.130
and Key Halls at George
Washington University

00:05:24.130 --> 00:05:25.600
and the University of Maryland

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:28.700
at College Park are
named for him.

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:33.470
Key also owned a country estate,
the farm where he was born,

00:05:33.470 --> 00:05:37.680
Terra Rubra, named for
the red clay of its soil

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:40.350
in Carroll County, Maryland,
a property that was added

00:05:40.350 --> 00:05:44.010
to the National Register
of Historic Places in 1978

00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:46.540
and is privately owned.

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:50.280
Key owned slaves, most of
whom worked at this farm

00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:53.800
but during his lifetime he was
actually considered a racial

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:57.340
humanitarian who pursued
dozens of legal cases

00:05:57.340 --> 00:06:01.040
to secure the freedom
of enslaved families.

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:04.040
Although he freed seven of his
slaves during his lifetime,

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:08.610
Key still owned eight enslaved
people at the time of his death.

00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:12.530
Believing that people of African
descent could never become full

00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:14.550
citizens, Key was the co-founder

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:16.960
of the American Colonization
Society,

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:19.050
which promoted the
settlement of freeborn

00:06:19.050 --> 00:06:22.520
and formerly enslaved
people in Africa.

00:06:25.150 --> 00:06:28.260
Frederick Douglass, renowned
for his influential memoirs

00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:33.560
and essays was known as an
eloquent and charismatic orator.

00:06:33.560 --> 00:06:35.890
His memoirs include "A
Narrative of the Life

00:06:35.890 --> 00:06:38.660
of Frederick Douglass, an
American Slave" published

00:06:38.660 --> 00:06:44.500
in 1845, "My Bondage and My
Freedom" 1855, and "The Life

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:50.510
and Times of Frederick
Douglass" 1881 revised in 1892.

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:53.520
Douglass moved to DC in 1872.

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:56.610
He served as DC's
recorder of deeds and later

00:06:56.610 --> 00:06:59.190
as consul general to Haiti.

00:06:59.190 --> 00:07:02.400
He is remembered with a bridge
across the Anacostia River named

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:05.740
in his honor and a statue
of Douglass represents DC

00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:09.530
in National Statuary
Hall in the US Capitol.

00:07:09.530 --> 00:07:12.220
Some of you may remember
we had to fight long

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:14.540
and hard to get our statue in.

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:17.920
Every state is represented
by two statues

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:20.510
in National Statuary Hall.

00:07:20.510 --> 00:07:23.020
We finally got one.

00:07:23.020 --> 00:07:27.970
But it is a lovely one,
Frederick Douglass.

00:07:27.970 --> 00:07:30.950
Douglass' house in
Anacostia is now preserved

00:07:30.950 --> 00:07:32.610
by the National Park Service.

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:36.140
It contains his original
furniture and books.

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:39.210
And in the rear, the National
Park Service has recreated his

00:07:39.210 --> 00:07:44.650
windowless stone studio, which
Douglass called the growlery.

00:07:44.650 --> 00:07:48.100
If you haven't been there,
I highly recommend the tour.

00:07:48.100 --> 00:07:52.100
2018 is the 200th
anniversary of Douglass' birth

00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:54.340
and the Park Service is
honoring him throughout the year

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:57.140
with a series of special events.

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:06.000
Walt Whitman lived in DC for
10 years, from 1863 to 1873.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.650
He's the author of the
masterpiece "Leaves of Grass",

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:13.490
a volume of poems he reedited
and republished numerous times

00:08:13.490 --> 00:08:18.460
between 1855 and 1891,
as well as "Drum Taps"

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:22.060
which we actually have
a rare first edition

00:08:22.060 --> 00:08:25.980
of on display here,
published in 1865,

00:08:25.980 --> 00:08:29.870
"Memoranda During the
War" and "Specimen Days".

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:34.580
None of his boarding house
residences in DC still stand.

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:37.610
I went through his
correspondence

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:39.920
which of course is
all held here.

00:08:39.920 --> 00:08:43.240
The Library of Congress
has the best collection

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:45.790
of items relating to
Whitman and the world.

00:08:45.790 --> 00:08:50.670
And I was able to find seven
different boarding houses

00:08:50.670 --> 00:08:54.800
where he rented rooms in the
10 years that he lived here,

00:08:54.800 --> 00:08:56.680
but they were all in
the old part of the city

00:08:56.680 --> 00:09:02.770
and they are now all the sites
of high-rise office buildings.

00:09:02.770 --> 00:09:06.090
But he is still remembered
in the city in other ways.

00:09:06.090 --> 00:09:08.100
A bust of him graces
the front desk

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:10.370
of the manuscript reading room
here at the Library of Congress

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:14.200
and his words are included in
several public art projects,

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:17.250
at two metro stations,
Dupont Circle

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:19.610
and Archives Navy Memorial,

00:09:19.610 --> 00:09:22.230
at Washington Reagan
National Airport

00:09:22.230 --> 00:09:25.180
and in the paving
stones at Freedom Plaza.

00:09:25.180 --> 00:09:26.780
In addition, a two block stretch

00:09:26.780 --> 00:09:30.180
of F Street Northwest has
been given the honorary name

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:32.800
of Walt Whitman Way.

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:37.220
Whitman volunteered as a
nurse visiting patients

00:09:37.220 --> 00:09:40.120
in over 50 temporary
war hospitals set

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:41.910
up across the city.

00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:45.180
Two months after arriving in
DC, Whitman wrote in a letter

00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:47.890
to his brother Jeff
about why he stayed.

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:50.750
I cannot give up
my hospitals yet.

00:09:50.750 --> 00:09:53.300
I never before had my
feelings so thoroughly

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:57.220
and so far permanently
absorbed to the very roots

00:09:57.220 --> 00:10:02.660
as by these huge swarms of
dear wounded, sick, dying boys.

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:05.060
I get very much attached
to some of them and many

00:10:05.060 --> 00:10:08.220
of them have come to depend
on seeing me and having me sit

00:10:08.220 --> 00:10:12.860
by them for a few minutes
as if for their lives.

00:10:12.860 --> 00:10:15.810
Long after the end of the
civil war, indeed for the rest

00:10:15.810 --> 00:10:19.090
of his life, Whitman continued
to write and publish poetry

00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:23.000
and prose on the war's
impact on American identity.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:24.860
Whitman even claimed
that "Leaves

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:26.420
of Grass" could not
have been written

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:29.770
without his wartime experiences
despite the fact the three

00:10:29.770 --> 00:10:31.800
earlier editions had
been published prior

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:34.540
to his moving to Washington.

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:37.440
For him, the civil war
and how the nation reacted

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:38.870
to it were more revealing

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:41.900
and more ennobling
than any other time.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:44.540
Of the years he spent
in DC, Whitman concluded

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:47.180
that I consider them
the greatest privilege

00:10:47.180 --> 00:10:50.440
and satisfaction with all
their feverish excitements

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:54.050
and physical deprivations
and of lamentable sights

00:10:54.050 --> 00:11:01.020
and of course the most
profound lesson of my life.

00:11:01.020 --> 00:11:04.150
Paul Laurence Dunbar was the
first African-American poet

00:11:04.150 --> 00:11:07.340
to become nationally known
and celebrated by both readers

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:10.400
of color and of mainstream
white audience.

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:14.600
His books of poems include "Oak
and Ivy", "Majors and Minors",

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:18.460
"Lyrics of a Lowly Life",
"Poems of Cabin and Field",

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:22.880
"When Malindy Sings" and
"Lyrics of Sunshine and Shadow".

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:25.420
His works of fiction
include "The Uncalled",

00:11:25.420 --> 00:11:28.180
"Folks from Dixie",
"The Strength of Gideon"

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:30.380
and "The Sport of the Gods".

00:11:30.380 --> 00:11:32.630
He also wrote the lyrics
for "In the Homie",

00:11:32.630 --> 00:11:35.550
the first musical written
and performed entirely

00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:39.140
by African-Americans
to appear on Broadway.

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:45.310
Dunbar moved to Washington,
DC in 1897 to take a job

00:11:45.310 --> 00:11:47.230
as an assistant librarian.

00:11:47.230 --> 00:11:52.100
Where? Here, of course, at
the Library of Congress.

00:11:52.100 --> 00:11:57.420
He hated the job and he left
it after less than a year.

00:11:57.420 --> 00:12:01.410
In 1898, he married another
writer, Alice Dunbar-Nelson,

00:12:01.410 --> 00:12:04.060
and they lived with Paul's
mother in two locations

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:06.950
in the LeDroit Park
neighborhood of DC.

00:12:06.950 --> 00:12:09.070
One of those houses, a row house

00:12:09.070 --> 00:12:12.850
at 1934 Fourth Street
Northwest still stands.

00:12:12.850 --> 00:12:17.520
It's not marked with a historic
plaque or recognized in any way.

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:20.490
I always wonder if the current
residents have any idea that two

00:12:20.490 --> 00:12:24.820
such eminent American writers
once lived in their house.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:30.050
In 1900, diagnosed with
tuberculosis and alcoholic,

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:33.030
he left the area to try
to regain his health.

00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:36.070
He returned to DC
briefly then Dunbar moved

00:12:36.070 --> 00:12:38.730
to his mother's home in
Dayton, Ohio where he died

00:12:38.730 --> 00:12:42.460
in 1906 at the age of 33.

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:43.760
He's remembered locally

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:47.210
with a DC public high
school named in his honor.

00:12:49.030 --> 00:12:52.240
Alice Dunbar-Nelson is
the author of "Violets

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:55.340
and Other Tales" and "The
Goodness of St. Rocque".

00:12:55.340 --> 00:12:58.560
She edited "Masterpieces
of Negro Eloquence"

00:12:58.560 --> 00:13:01.920
and the "Dunbar Speaker
and Entertainer".

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:04.160
Dunbar-Nelson was
a regular columnist

00:13:04.160 --> 00:13:07.340
for the Pittsburgh Courier
and the Washington Eagle

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:10.480
and co-editor of the AME Review.

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:13.340
She also served as
Mid-Atlantic field organizer

00:13:13.340 --> 00:13:15.810
for women's suffrage,
a representative

00:13:15.810 --> 00:13:17.870
for the women's committee
on the council of defense

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:22.530
and was a popular speaker
to a wide range of groups.

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:24.680
She helped to establish
the industrial school

00:13:24.680 --> 00:13:28.480
for colored girls in
Marshallton, Delaware.

00:13:30.430 --> 00:13:33.040
The Dunbar marriage
was not a happy one.

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:37.420
Dunbar was physically abusive
and the pair separated in 1902

00:13:37.420 --> 00:13:40.190
and Dunbar died four
years later.

00:13:40.190 --> 00:13:43.960
Dunbar-Nelson subsequently
moved to Maryland and Delaware.

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:45.790
She married two more times

00:13:45.790 --> 00:13:48.370
but always retained her eminent
first husband's last time

00:13:48.370 --> 00:13:50.460
as it helped her
to get publishing

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:52.410
and speaking engagements.

00:13:52.410 --> 00:13:56.280
She also depended
on royalty checks

00:13:56.280 --> 00:14:00.650
which she split with
Dunbar's mother.

00:14:00.650 --> 00:14:02.860
Her third marriage
to Robert J. Nelson,

00:14:02.860 --> 00:14:05.610
a journalist, was her happiest.

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:14.430
Mark Twain lived in DC in 1867
working briefly as secretary

00:14:14.430 --> 00:14:18.450
to Senator William
Morris Stewart of Nevada.

00:14:18.450 --> 00:14:20.900
He lived in a boarding
house favored by journalists

00:14:20.900 --> 00:14:24.570
where he terrorized his
landlady Virginia Wells.

00:14:24.570 --> 00:14:28.280
According to Senator Stewart
who also lived at that address,

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:32.060
he would lurch around the halls
pretending to be intoxicated.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:34.650
He would burn the light
in his bedroom all night.

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:38.340
Pretty soon, he took to smoking
cigars in bed and ruined all

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:41.090
of her sheets with burn holes.

00:14:41.090 --> 00:14:42.960
Twain finished the
manuscript of his book

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:46.260
"The Innocence Abroad"
while living in DC.

00:14:46.260 --> 00:14:49.670
His experiences in DC directly
inspired his next novel,

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:52.840
"The Gilded Age", a satire
of the city's political

00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:57.150
and social life, co-written
with Charles Dudley Warner.

00:14:57.150 --> 00:15:00.880
His label for the post-civil
war period has stuck.

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:04.080
It describes the economic
growth, widening divide

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:06.820
between the rich and poor
and political corruption

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:09.500
that are hallmarks of that era.

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:17.230
Sinclair Lewis, famous for his
novels about small town life

00:15:17.230 --> 00:15:20.510
in the Midwest did his most
productive writing during the

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:22.330
period he lived in
Washington, DC.

00:15:22.330 --> 00:15:25.880
Seems like he needed to leave
the Midwest in order to be able

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:27.180
to write about the Midwest.

00:15:27.180 --> 00:15:30.720
He wrote his classic books
"Main Street", "Babbitt"

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:33.730
and "Arrowsmith" while
living in the capital and two

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:37.330
of the homes he rented
still stand.

00:15:37.330 --> 00:15:41.690
The first American writer to win
the Noble Prize for Literature

00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:45.670
in 1930, Lewis wrote
23 novels as well

00:15:45.670 --> 00:15:47.940
as plays and short fiction.

00:15:47.940 --> 00:15:51.460
His other novels include
"Elmer Gantry" and "Dodsworth".

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:55.820
We have "Dodsworth" on display
here, both adapted into movies,

00:15:55.820 --> 00:15:59.260
as well as "It Can't Happen
Here", "King's Blood Royal"

00:15:59.260 --> 00:16:02.000
and the posthumous
"World So Wide".

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.190
H.L. Mencken characterized
him as a red haired tornado

00:16:06.190 --> 00:16:09.020
from the Minnesota Wilds.

00:16:09.020 --> 00:16:12.350
"Main Street" sold an
estimated two million copies

00:16:12.350 --> 00:16:17.030
within the first few years after
publication and made Lewis rich.

00:16:17.030 --> 00:16:20.650
Biographer Mark Schorer states
it was the most sensational

00:16:20.650 --> 00:16:23.920
event in 20th century
American publishing history.

00:16:23.920 --> 00:16:27.470
The printers could not keep up
with orders and publishers had

00:16:27.470 --> 00:16:31.440
for a while to ration out
copies to book sellers.

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:36.390
Langston Hughes lived
in Washington,

00:16:36.390 --> 00:16:40.970
DC for a very short time,
one year and four months.

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:44.680
During that time, he was
depressed and unsettled,

00:16:44.680 --> 00:16:46.640
yet it was an extremely
important time

00:16:46.640 --> 00:16:49.220
in the poet's early development.

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:53.360
While residing in DC, Hughes
won his first poetry competition

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:56.500
and gave his first
public poetry readings.

00:16:56.500 --> 00:16:58.810
He got a contract for
his first book of poems

00:16:58.810 --> 00:17:01.160
from Alfred A. Knopf
in New York,

00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:03.840
finished that book
manuscript and published

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:07.050
"The Weary Blues"
in February 1926.

00:17:07.050 --> 00:17:08.670
He also wrote most of the poems

00:17:08.670 --> 00:17:11.060
that would appear
in his second book.

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:13.350
He developed friendships
with prominent writers

00:17:13.350 --> 00:17:17.090
and intellectuals such as Alain
Locke and Carl Van Vechten

00:17:17.090 --> 00:17:20.280
and also with numerous
younger writers,

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:22.070
and some of those
friendships he would keep

00:17:22.070 --> 00:17:24.760
for the rest of his life.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:27.090
His experience in
Washington was also crucial

00:17:27.090 --> 00:17:29.030
to Hughes for another reason.

00:17:29.030 --> 00:17:31.160
It solidified and
deepened his commitment

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:33.200
to the African-American
working class,

00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:34.640
which would influence
his writing

00:17:34.640 --> 00:17:36.910
for the rest of his life.

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:39.620
Hughes' use of vernacular
English and the rhythm

00:17:39.620 --> 00:17:42.230
of the blues widely
influenced modernism

00:17:42.230 --> 00:17:45.050
and the course of
American letters.

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:47.930
Two of his residences
still stand, a private home

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:53.070
at 1749 S Street Northwest,
again, not marked with a plaque.

00:17:53.070 --> 00:17:54.910
No one would know.

00:17:54.910 --> 00:17:59.950
And that's where he lived
one winter with his mother

00:17:59.950 --> 00:18:03.020
and his stepbrother Kit in 1925

00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:06.650
in two unheated rooms
on the second floor.

00:18:06.650 --> 00:18:10.150
They had a movable heater
which they took turns moving

00:18:10.150 --> 00:18:12.770
from one room to the next.

00:18:12.770 --> 00:18:15.870
And also the 12th Street YMCA,

00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:19.270
now the third Thurgood Marshall
Center for Service and Heritage

00:18:19.270 --> 00:18:23.400
at 1816 12th Street Northwest
where Hughes briefly lived

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:27.520
in a tiny single occupancy
room on the third floor.

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:32.640
If you go to the Thurgood
Marshall Center, you can--

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:35.760
if it's during a weekday,
you can ring the doorbell

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:37.570
and they will let you in.

00:18:37.570 --> 00:18:40.190
They've got displays
in the lobby

00:18:40.190 --> 00:18:43.340
of the first floor recreating
what the lobby would have looked

00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:44.640
like during Hughes' time.

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:46.970
And on the second floor,
they've recreated one

00:18:46.970 --> 00:18:49.380
of the single occupancy rooms

00:18:49.380 --> 00:18:53.320
and they actually very sweetly
put in a manual typewriter.

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:54.800
So I think they are trying

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:58.100
to say this is what Langston
Hughes' room could have

00:18:58.100 --> 00:18:59.420
looked like.

00:18:59.420 --> 00:19:04.900
But it's worth a trip if you're
in the U Street neighborhood.

00:19:08.620 --> 00:19:11.240
Like Langston Hughes,
Duke Ellington

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:14.800
and so many other artists of
the Harlem renaissance period,

00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:18.150
Zora Neale Hurston
began her career in DC.

00:19:18.150 --> 00:19:23.050
She attended Howard University
from 1919 through 1924,

00:19:23.050 --> 00:19:26.770
earning an associates degree
and embracing campus life.

00:19:26.770 --> 00:19:30.320
She joined a sorority, the
campus theater group and wrote

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:33.130
for the campus literary
journal, "The Stylus",

00:19:33.130 --> 00:19:35.240
where she published
her first short story.

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:41.540
While a full time student at
Howard, Hurston also held jobs

00:19:41.540 --> 00:19:44.030
as a manicurist and waitress.

00:19:44.030 --> 00:19:48.570
Hurston owned only one dress
when she first arrived in DC

00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:50.190
but soon earned enough to enter

00:19:50.190 --> 00:19:53.480
into the city's elite
African-American circles.

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:55.920
She was a regular at the
Saturday nighters salon

00:19:55.920 --> 00:19:58.170
in the home of Georgia
Douglas Johnson

00:19:58.170 --> 00:20:00.770
and developed friendships with
other writers and scholars

00:20:00.770 --> 00:20:03.170
that would last the
rest of her life.

00:20:03.170 --> 00:20:05.850
After DC, she moved to New
York where she earned a degree

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:10.380
in anthropology from
Barnard College in 1927.

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:13.100
That same year, she was awarded
a grant from the Association

00:20:13.100 --> 00:20:15.920
for the Study of Negro life
and history based in DC

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:19.140
to do anthropological
work in Florida,

00:20:19.140 --> 00:20:22.820
which led to the publication of
her second book, "Mules and Men"

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:28.080
in 1935, as well as the
recent posthumous publication

00:20:28.080 --> 00:20:30.890
of "Barracoon" earlier
this year.

00:20:30.890 --> 00:20:35.160
That was also done on
that same research grant.

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:39.310
Neither of her former DC
homes is marked with a plaque.

00:20:39.310 --> 00:20:42.230
We're getting a theme here.

00:20:42.230 --> 00:20:44.800
I do think that DC
needs to do a better job

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:48.630
of claiming our fantastic
rich literary history.

00:20:48.630 --> 00:20:52.700
You can find all of these
writers and more in my book.

00:20:52.700 --> 00:20:55.850
I'm really pleased with
how the book came out.

00:20:55.850 --> 00:20:59.750
The University of Virginia Press
did a gorgeous job with the maps

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:02.670
and combining historic
photographs, many of them

00:21:02.670 --> 00:21:05.310
from the collections of
the Library of Congress

00:21:05.310 --> 00:21:09.360
with contemporary photographs
taken by a local writer

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:10.850
and visual artist Dan Vera.

00:21:10.850 --> 00:21:15.930
And I can take questions.

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:20.660
I do hope that you
will want to take some

00:21:20.660 --> 00:21:24.870
of the walking tours
yourself, do some exploration.

