00:30:14.360 --> 00:30:15.660
to be included in that.

00:30:15.660 --> 00:30:16.960
We don't want tourists to
come up knocking on our door."

00:30:16.960 --> 00:30:18.260
And Dan and I just-- and we
could hardly keep in the--

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:19.560
our glee as we were imagining
like Auslander groupies.

00:30:19.560 --> 00:30:20.860
No. We assured him it was not
ever, ever going to happen.

00:30:20.860 --> 00:30:22.160
But we have had other
people who, you know,

00:30:22.160 --> 00:30:23.460
for example we were
photographing the childhood home

00:30:23.460 --> 00:30:24.760
of Philip K. Dick and the
homeowner's grandson came out

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:26.060
and he had never heard of the
author until we mentioned some

00:30:26.060 --> 00:30:27.360
of the movies that had
been made from his books

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:28.660
and then he got extremely
excited and pull--

00:30:28.660 --> 00:30:29.960
ran in, got his grandmother,
pulled her out to talk--

00:30:29.960 --> 00:30:31.260
you know, so you know,
that goes both ways.

00:30:31.260 --> 00:30:32.560
But I will say that what I
consider the most important

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:33.860
extant site of the Harlem
renaissance era is a private

00:30:33.860 --> 00:30:37.800
home that was owned by Georgia
Douglas Johnson on S Street,

00:30:37.800 --> 00:30:40.940
so near the historic
U Street neighborhood.

00:30:40.940 --> 00:30:42.860
It's at S and 15.

00:30:42.860 --> 00:30:47.670
And I have led a Harlem
renaissance walking tour

00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:51.120
or versions of a Harlem
renaissance walking tour for,

00:30:51.120 --> 00:30:54.100
I don't know, a decade
or two now.

00:30:54.100 --> 00:30:56.520
And so I always would stop
in front of that house.

00:30:56.520 --> 00:30:59.480
And one of the former owners,
every time I would come

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:02.740
out with a group of--
who were taking a tour,

00:31:02.740 --> 00:31:06.620
they would make a big point
of shutting their blinds.

00:31:06.620 --> 00:31:09.840
They hated that they
were living in a house

00:31:09.840 --> 00:31:11.970
that was so recognized.

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:14.020
But they sold the house.

00:31:14.020 --> 00:31:18.640
They moved away and the new
owners have embraced it.

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:22.460
So, you know, I take
pleasure in the fact

00:31:22.460 --> 00:31:27.690
that Georgia Douglas Johnson
will outlast any modern owner

00:31:27.690 --> 00:31:29.650
of the house.

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:31.450
&gt;&gt; Don.

00:31:31.450 --> 00:31:38.560
[ Inaudible ]

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:40.090
Thank you.

00:31:40.090 --> 00:31:42.680
&gt;&gt; Don: Just this idea of
tracking down all the places

00:31:42.680 --> 00:31:44.930
where Walt Whitman
lived is [inaudible].

00:31:44.930 --> 00:31:46.230
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: It's
amazing to me

00:31:46.230 --> 00:31:47.890
that no one has done
this before me.

00:31:47.890 --> 00:31:52.830
It-- so with the Whitman
research, I will tell you

00:31:52.830 --> 00:31:57.440
that the biggest help
to me was going back

00:31:57.440 --> 00:32:00.140
to the correspondence
he had with his mother.

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:01.440
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:32:01.440 --> 00:32:03.400
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Because
who else do you write

00:32:03.400 --> 00:32:06.930
to about how the boarding
house lady treats you

00:32:06.930 --> 00:32:11.310
and your bed is lumpy and
if the food is good or,

00:32:11.310 --> 00:32:12.610
you know, et cetera.

00:32:12.610 --> 00:32:15.330
So those letters were just
a treasure trove for me.

00:32:15.330 --> 00:32:20.680
However, before 1870,
none of the addresses

00:32:20.680 --> 00:32:23.190
in DC were regularized.

00:32:23.190 --> 00:32:27.040
So what I mean by that
is as houses were built,

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:29.410
they were just numbered
as they went along.

00:32:29.410 --> 00:32:33.510
It wasn't until 1870
that they decided that--

00:32:33.510 --> 00:32:39.440
so for example if you live
in the 300 block of L Street,

00:32:39.440 --> 00:32:44.020
then you know that you go to
L Street between 3rd and 4th.

00:32:45.100 --> 00:32:47.260
That didn't have that
regularized system,

00:32:47.260 --> 00:32:48.860
didn't happen until 1870.

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:54.440
So, every address in the city
prior to 1870 had to be changed.

00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:55.740
And-- So the hardest thing--

00:32:55.740 --> 00:32:57.040
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:32:57.040 --> 00:33:00.320
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: -- for me
was translating the earlier

00:33:00.320 --> 00:33:03.250
addresses into the
current addresses.

00:33:03.250 --> 00:33:06.520
&gt;&gt; Were there-- were the city
directories of [inaudible].

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:11.370
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Yes, so the
1870 city directory gave very

00:33:11.370 --> 00:33:19.380
elaborate instructions on how
to translate addresses in each--

00:33:19.380 --> 00:33:20.680
There were different
parts of the city

00:33:20.680 --> 00:33:22.280
where it was done
slightly differently.

00:33:22.280 --> 00:33:24.510
So it gave these elaborate--

00:33:24.510 --> 00:33:27.700
But I had to go back to
the based real estate maps

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:30.690
and actually look at
plats to make sure.

00:33:30.690 --> 00:33:32.810
So, that was tedious.

00:33:32.810 --> 00:33:38.190
&gt;&gt; Well, a more general approach
is-- and when-- for your period,

00:33:38.190 --> 00:33:42.760
would you say that there is--

00:33:42.760 --> 00:33:46.530
was a literary poetry
of Washington

00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:51.860
and how would you define
that and if there wasn't

00:33:51.860 --> 00:33:56.260
such a thing, why
it wasn't there.

00:33:56.260 --> 00:33:57.560
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Yeah.

00:33:57.560 --> 00:33:58.860
So yes, the answer is yes.

00:33:58.860 --> 00:34:02.070
But part of the weirdness
of our city is that prior

00:34:02.070 --> 00:34:07.560
to the civil war there
was a small group

00:34:07.560 --> 00:34:12.840
of year round residents and
then there was this huge group

00:34:12.840 --> 00:34:15.780
of people who came just
for the winter season

00:34:15.780 --> 00:34:17.940
when Congress is in session.

00:34:17.940 --> 00:34:22.470
And so there was this sort of
seasonal literary community

00:34:22.470 --> 00:34:26.260
that swelled and then there
was this modest, you know,

00:34:26.260 --> 00:34:33.710
sort of small town
older group of citizens.

00:34:33.710 --> 00:34:39.230
So that really affected
literary culture quite a bit

00:34:39.230 --> 00:34:40.770
in the city's early days.

00:34:40.770 --> 00:34:44.960
You know, it's harder to
build community with people

00:34:44.960 --> 00:34:47.830
who are only here
part of the year.

00:34:47.830 --> 00:34:52.740
So, that was one thing that
sort of kept things very small.

00:34:52.740 --> 00:34:57.610
And initially DC didn't have
the-- it didn't have theaters

00:34:57.610 --> 00:34:59.910
and bookstores and, you
know, the types of places

00:34:59.910 --> 00:35:03.480
where a literary
community might gather.

00:35:03.480 --> 00:35:07.340
So it really wasn't
until after the civil war

00:35:07.340 --> 00:35:12.580
that we became a
city of any size.

00:35:12.580 --> 00:35:15.500
And that's when things
really started to change.

00:35:15.500 --> 00:35:21.480
&gt;&gt; What were the markers of
the literary [inaudible]?

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:26.030
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Well, I would
say the main markers were places

00:35:26.030 --> 00:35:27.590
where writers could gather.

00:35:27.590 --> 00:35:33.270
So that would be the rise
of salons in people's homes.

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:36.840
That would be certainly
the rise of institutions

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:42.290
such as Howard University,
the American Negro Academy.

00:35:42.290 --> 00:35:48.210
You know it's at-- but
the institutions are--

00:35:48.210 --> 00:35:51.810
help build community.

00:35:51.810 --> 00:35:57.630
Certainly there were a lot
of writers in the early days

00:35:57.630 --> 00:36:00.600
of the literary community
who were journalists,

00:36:00.600 --> 00:36:02.540
as well as creative writers.

00:36:02.540 --> 00:36:06.870
So a big part of sort
of a meeting house

00:36:06.870 --> 00:36:10.100
for writers would
have been the--

00:36:10.100 --> 00:36:13.490
what was called newspaper row.

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:16.460
&gt;&gt; There were towns and bars.

00:36:16.460 --> 00:36:17.760
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: There
were, yeah.

00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:20.220
Actually for the
journalists in the early days,

00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:25.260
a lot of them were hanging
out in bars in the block

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:30.030
where the National
Theater is today.

00:36:30.030 --> 00:36:34.560
Those were favored
by journalists.

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:40.750
It's where the gin rickey
was first developed that's--

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:43.270
well, one of our-- one
of our claims to fame is

00:36:43.270 --> 00:36:47.810
that what was made up here
and, you know, that the bar

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:52.510
at the Willard Hotel
was another place.

00:36:52.510 --> 00:36:54.100
Yeah, so.

00:36:54.100 --> 00:36:56.380
[ Inaudible ]

00:36:56.380 --> 00:36:59.150
The National Press Club
came, yeah, much later.

00:36:59.150 --> 00:37:05.660
I don't-- I don't know the exact
date but interestingly part

00:37:05.660 --> 00:37:09.290
of what was then called
newspaper row is now the site

00:37:09.290 --> 00:37:12.630
of that building, the
National Press Club.

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:14.650
&gt;&gt; Which is all male
[inaudible].

00:37:14.650 --> 00:37:16.360
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Right,
of course.

00:37:16.360 --> 00:37:19.820
&gt;&gt; We have a question
at the back.

00:37:19.820 --> 00:37:21.120
Go ahead [inaudible].

00:37:21.120 --> 00:37:22.420
&gt;&gt; I have two questions, one--

00:37:22.420 --> 00:37:25.550
I think British [inaudible]
Washington, DC was the discovery

00:37:25.550 --> 00:37:28.560
that Francis Scott Fitzgerald
[inaudible] were very,

00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:29.860
you know, [inaudible].

00:37:29.860 --> 00:37:32.530
And so I'm just wondering,

00:37:32.530 --> 00:37:36.700
are there any things
literary people buried in DC?

00:37:36.700 --> 00:37:38.000
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Oh yeah.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:42.130
&gt;&gt; And secondly, can you
talk about Henry Adams?

00:37:42.130 --> 00:37:43.430
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Oh, sure.

00:37:43.430 --> 00:37:47.420
Yeah. So the reason that
the Fitzgeralds were here is

00:37:47.420 --> 00:37:54.170
because it was his family
that had lived here.

00:37:54.170 --> 00:37:59.660
Yes, his family had lived here
so they were actually married

00:37:59.660 --> 00:38:05.810
in DC in his parents' house
or his grandparents' house.

00:38:05.810 --> 00:38:07.720
So they had family
connections here.

00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:10.150
And then you know of
course their daughter,

00:38:10.150 --> 00:38:12.650
Scottie, settled in DC.

00:38:12.650 --> 00:38:15.870
So, weirdly it was just
a family connection

00:38:15.870 --> 00:38:19.040
but they didn't live here.

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:21.040
They never lived here.

00:38:21.040 --> 00:38:28.700
But there are some other sort
of surprising burials here

00:38:28.700 --> 00:38:33.500
where writers wanted
to be in the capital,

00:38:33.500 --> 00:38:35.450
in the sort of center
of, you know,

00:38:35.450 --> 00:38:39.990
but didn't necessarily have
a connection to the city.

00:38:39.990 --> 00:38:43.210
What is the name of the
writer who wrote the poem

00:38:43.210 --> 00:38:46.510
"Home Sweet Home" which
became a famous lyric?

00:38:46.510 --> 00:38:50.340
[ Inaudible ]

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:51.640
Yes, right.

00:38:51.640 --> 00:38:54.450
Is he never lived in the city
but he wanted his remains to be.

00:38:54.450 --> 00:38:57.520
You know, so there
is examples of that

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:02.260
which is sort of fascinating.

00:39:02.260 --> 00:39:03.760
I don't really understand
the appeal

00:39:03.760 --> 00:39:05.630
but at that, you know, OK.

00:39:05.630 --> 00:39:08.930
And then your second question
was about Henry Adams.

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:19.670
So Henry Adams, he lived in DC
after he retired from teaching

00:39:19.670 --> 00:39:24.500
at a-- He was a history teacher
at Harvard and the editor

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:25.860
of the North American review.

00:39:25.860 --> 00:39:32.020
And he had come to DC
of course as a child

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:36.720
and visited his grandparents
and his great grandparents and,

00:39:36.720 --> 00:39:39.610
you know, he had-- He was part
of this big political dynasty.

00:39:39.610 --> 00:39:44.280
So he knew if he moved here,
he would have cache right away.

00:39:44.280 --> 00:39:46.680
And he lived in a couple

00:39:46.680 --> 00:39:50.190
of different residences
in Lafayette Square.

00:39:50.190 --> 00:39:57.500
The last house, the
one that he had built

00:39:57.500 --> 00:40:01.230
for himself is now the site
of the Hay-Adams Hotel.

00:40:01.230 --> 00:40:03.370
And that's why it's
called the Hay-Adams Hotel.

00:40:03.370 --> 00:40:07.050
It was the site of his house
and his best friend's house,

00:40:07.050 --> 00:40:15.070
John Hay, who was another writer
but is famously known as one

00:40:15.070 --> 00:40:18.480
of the two personal
secretaries to Abraham Lincoln.

00:40:18.480 --> 00:40:21.010
Later became Secretary
of State under a couple

00:40:21.010 --> 00:40:22.620
of different presidents.

00:40:22.620 --> 00:40:28.070
I'm getting sort of way
late here but the only house

00:40:28.070 --> 00:40:33.330
of Henry Adams is-- that still
stands is a place that he--

00:40:33.330 --> 00:40:36.720
his father rented
for one winter.

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:40.620
His father was a
senator and he served

00:40:40.620 --> 00:40:42.950
as his father's personal
secretary

00:40:42.950 --> 00:40:46.040
and it's now the Arts
Club of Washington.

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:48.800
So that that's the one place.

00:40:48.800 --> 00:40:54.090
And of course he's buried
here in Rock Creek Cemetery

00:40:54.090 --> 00:41:01.320
under a monument that is
probably the most important

00:41:01.320 --> 00:41:04.830
piece of funerary art
in the entire nation.

00:41:04.830 --> 00:41:08.790
If you have not made the
field trip to go see it, I--

00:41:08.790 --> 00:41:13.130
it's part of the Henry Adams
tour in my book but I just--

00:41:13.130 --> 00:41:16.670
I think it's stunning.

00:41:16.670 --> 00:41:18.230
It's worth seeing.

00:41:18.230 --> 00:41:24.980
And you know, Henry Adams was
such a snob, you know, he--

00:41:24.980 --> 00:41:26.660
there is absolutely no way

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:30.890
that I would have been
acceptable to him as a person.

00:41:30.890 --> 00:41:33.640
He-- not just because
I'm a woman

00:41:33.640 --> 00:41:35.760
but also because I'm Jewish.

00:41:35.760 --> 00:41:40.240
He hated Jews, very
anti-Semitic.

00:41:40.240 --> 00:41:44.480
And yet, his writing is just--

00:41:44.480 --> 00:41:47.530
I mean what an exquisite
prose stylist.

00:41:47.530 --> 00:41:51.850
He's so worth reading and
you know he's dead now.

00:41:51.850 --> 00:41:56.270
We don't have to deal with what
a nasty human being he was.

00:41:56.270 --> 00:42:01.170
But his books, especially "The
Education of Henry Adams",

00:42:01.170 --> 00:42:04.960
his memoir and "Democracy", I
feel like everyone should read.

00:42:04.960 --> 00:42:07.370
And "Democracy" is fun.

00:42:07.370 --> 00:42:09.850
It's a fun read.

00:42:09.850 --> 00:42:11.150
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:42:11.150 --> 00:42:12.450
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Thanks.

00:42:12.450 --> 00:42:13.750
Thanks for asking.

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:15.050
&gt;&gt; John.

00:42:15.050 --> 00:42:16.350
&gt;&gt; John: This is [inaudible] to
go back to the previous section

00:42:16.350 --> 00:42:17.650
about [inaudible] but talking

00:42:17.650 --> 00:42:19.790
about literary cultures
in Washington.

00:42:19.790 --> 00:42:21.090
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Yeah.

00:42:21.090 --> 00:42:22.390
&gt;&gt; John: It seems to me,

00:42:22.390 --> 00:42:27.360
and this is partly [inaudible]
numerous appearances on the web,

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:30.740
there it makes two and
second [inaudible].

00:42:30.740 --> 00:42:32.470
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Oh, yeah,
yeah, there's cultures.

00:42:32.470 --> 00:42:33.770
Right.

00:42:33.770 --> 00:42:36.100
&gt;&gt; John: And I'm struck by
the fact that from [inaudible]

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:39.730
to civil war on into the 1950s,

00:42:39.730 --> 00:42:49.720
there's a very small continuous
African-American intellectual

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:51.670
and cultural tradition

00:42:51.670 --> 00:42:54.530
in Washington Center
throughout the [inaudible].

00:42:54.530 --> 00:42:55.830
&gt;&gt; Kim Roberts: Right.

00:42:55.830 --> 00:42:57.130
So start-- yeah.

00:42:57.130 --> 00:43:01.010
Starting in-- during the
civil war the city was a draw

00:43:01.010 --> 00:43:04.420
for intellectuals of
color and that continued

00:43:04.420 --> 00:43:07.250
through reconstruction
and long afterwards.

00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:12.450
And this is one of the
things that I really--

00:43:12.450 --> 00:43:15.580
I wish this story
were better known

00:43:15.580 --> 00:43:18.530
and we did a better
job of claiming.

00:43:18.530 --> 00:43:22.290
When you compare us to New York,
this city was more affordable

00:43:22.290 --> 00:43:26.650
and so the neighborhoods in
the middle of the city, Shaw,

00:43:26.650 --> 00:43:29.080
Pleasant Plains, LeDroit Park.

00:43:29.080 --> 00:43:33.160
Those mid-city neighborhoods
were places where people

00:43:33.160 --> 00:43:36.010
of color could afford
to own not just rent.

00:43:36.010 --> 00:43:39.590
And that made a middle
class lifestyle here

00:43:39.590 --> 00:43:44.300
in DC more attainable than any
other major city in the US,

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:48.820
plus the education
that was offered here.

00:43:48.820 --> 00:43:51.780
So I don't know if
you're familiar

00:43:51.780 --> 00:43:53.780
with M Street High School.

00:43:53.780 --> 00:43:56.920
It's the forerunner to
today's Dunbar High.

00:43:56.920 --> 00:44:01.800
But it was not just
the top high school

00:44:01.800 --> 00:44:08.340
in DC during segregated public
schooling, it was the top school

00:44:08.340 --> 00:44:10.930
for students of color
in the entire nation.

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:14.250
And there were many
families who moved to DC just

00:44:14.250 --> 00:44:19.400
for the opportunity to send
their children to that school.

00:44:19.400 --> 00:44:21.890
Plus of course we had
Howard University.

00:44:21.890 --> 00:44:27.600
Partly because of
the strange story

00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:32.500
of how slaves were freed
first in DC before the rest

00:44:32.500 --> 00:44:33.800
of the nation,

00:44:33.800 --> 00:44:37.640
the African-American
intellectual community felt

00:44:37.640 --> 00:44:43.160
like people of color had gotten
a head start here in the city

00:44:43.160 --> 00:44:47.200
and that we needed to
be a national model.

00:44:47.200 --> 00:44:53.520
Plus, you know, there were good
paying prestigious jobs here

00:44:53.520 --> 00:44:55.180
especially in the
federal government

00:44:55.180 --> 00:44:56.580
that people of color could get.

00:44:56.580 --> 00:45:00.170
There were, you know--
this was--

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:05.290
I will say during the
Harlem renaissance period,

00:45:05.290 --> 00:45:11.790
a lot of writers and artists who
started here moved to New York

00:45:11.790 --> 00:45:15.790
but a lot stayed and in
general, the people who moved

00:45:15.790 --> 00:45:19.520
